approximately m sentences we used vocabulary of k tokens for the wsj only setting vocabulary of k tokens for the semisupervised setting we performed only small number of experiments to select the dropout both attention residual section learning rates beam size on the section development set other parameters remained unchanged from the englishtogerman base translation model during inference we increased the maximum output length to input length we used beam size of for both wsj only the semisupervised setting our results table show that despite the lack of taskspecific tuning our model performs sur prisingly well yielding better results than previously reported models with the exception of the recurrent neural network grammar contrast to rnn sequencetosequence models the transformer outperforms the berkeley parser even when training only on the wsj training set of k sentences conclusion this work we presented the transformer the first sequence transduction model based entirely on attention replacing the recurrent layers most commonly used encoderdecoder architectures with multiheaded selfattention for translation tasks the transformer can be trained significantly faster than architectures based on recurrent or convolutional layers on both wmt englishtogerman wmt englishtofrench translation tasks we achieve new state of the art the former task our best model outperforms even previously reported ensembles we are excited about the future of attentionbased models plan to apply them to other tasks we plan to extend the transformer to problems involving input output modalities other than text to investigate local restricted attention mechanisms to efficiently handle large inputs outputs such as images audio video making generation less sequential is another research goals of ours the code we used to train evaluate our models is available at httpsgithubcom tensorflowtensortensor acknowledgements we are grateful to nal kalchbrenner stephan gouws for their illiapolosukhingmailcom abstract the dominant sequence transduction models are based on complex recurrent or convolutional neural networks that include encoder decoder the best performing models connect the encoder decoder through attention mechanism we propose new simple network architecture the transformer based solely on attention mechanisms dispensing with recurrence convolutions entirely experiments on two machine translation tasks show these models to be superior quality while being more parallelizable requiring significantly less time to train our model achieves bleu on the wmt english togerman translation task improving over the existing best results including ensembles by over bleu on the wmt englishtofrench translation task our model establishes new singlemodel stateoftheart bleu score of after training for days on eight gpus small fraction of the training costs of the best models from the literature we show that the transformer generalizes well to other tasks by applying it successfully to english constituency parsing both with large limited training data introduction recurrent neural networks long shortterm memory gated recurrent neural networks particular have been firmly established as state of the art approaches sequence modeling equal contribution listing order is random jakob proposed replacing rnns with selfattention started the effort to evaluate this idea ashish with illia designed implemented the first transformer models has been crucially involved every aspect of this work noam proposed scaled dotproduct attention multihead attention the parameterfree position representation became the other person involved nearly every detail niki designed implemented tuned evaluated countless model variants our original codebase tensortensor llion experimented with novel model variants responsible for our initial codebase efficient inference visualizations lukasz aidan spent countless long days designing various parts of implementing tensortensor replacing our earlier codebase greatly improving results massively accelerating our research work performed while at google brain work performed while at google research st conference on neural information processing systems nips long beach ca usa,

transduction problems such as language modeling machine translation numerous efforts have since continued to push the boundaries of recurrent language models encoderdecoder architectures recurrent models typically factor computation along the symbol positions of the input output sequences aligning the positions to steps computation time they generate sequence of hidden states h as function of the previous hidden state h the input for position t this inherently sequential nature precludes parallelization within training examples which becomes critical at longer sequence lengths as memory constraints limit batching across examples recent work has achieved significant improvements computational efficiency through factorization tricks conditional computation while improving model performance case of the latter the fundamental constraint of sequential computation however remains attention mechanisms have become integral part of compelling sequence modeling transduc tion models various tasks allowing modeling of dependencies without regard to their distance the input or output sequences but few cases however such attention mechanisms are used conjunction with recurrent network this work we propose the transformer model architecture eschewing recurrence instead relying entirely on attention mechanism to draw global dependencies between input output the transformer allows for significantly more parallelization can reach new state of the art translation quality after being trained for as little as twelve hours on eight p gpus background the goal of reducing sequential computation forms the foundation of the extended neural gpu bytenet convss of which use convolutional neural networks as basic building block computing hidden representations parallel for input output positions these models the number of operations required to relate signals from two arbitrary input or output positions grows the distance between positions linearly for convss logarithmically for bytenet this makes it more difficult to learn dependencies between distant positions the transformer this is reduced to constant number of operations albeit at the cost of reduced effective resolution due to averaging attentionweighted positions effect we counteract with multihead attention as described sectionb selfattention sometimes called intraattention is attention mechanism relating different positions of single sequence order to compute representation of the sequence selfattention has been used successfully variety of tasks including reading comprehension abstractive summarization textual entailment learning taskindependent sentence representations endtoend memory networks are based on recurrent attention mechanism instead of sequence aligned recurrence have been shown to perform well on simplelanguage question answering language modeling tasks to the best of our knowledge however the transformer is the first transduction model relying entirely on selfattention to compute representations of its input output without using sequence aligned rnns or convolution the following sections we describe the transformer motivate selfattention discuss its advantages over models such as l model architecture most competitive neural sequence transduction models have encoderdecoder structure here the encoder maps input sequence of symbol representations to sequence of continuous representations z zn given z the decoder then generates output sequence yj ym of symbols one element at time at each step the model is autoregressive consuming the previously generated symbols as additional input when generating the next the transformer follows this overall architecture using stacked selfattention pointwise fully connected layers multihead attention allows the model to jointly attend to information from different representation subspaces at different positions with single attention head averaging inhibits this multiheadq kv concathead head w where head attentionqw kw vw where the projections are parameter matrices w re we rmarxde yy ramon xd w ride xdmoaet this work we employ h parallel attention layers or heads for each of these we use dy dy amoaeih due to the reduced dimension of each head the total computational cost is similar to that of singlehead attention with full dimensionality applications of attention our model the transformer uses multihead attention three different ways encoderdecoder attention layers the queries come from the previous decoder layer the memory keys values come from the output of the encoder this allows every position the decoder to attend over positions the input sequence this mimics the typical encoderdecoder attention mechanisms sequencetosequence models such as the encoder contains selfattention layers selfattention layer of the keys values queries come from the same place this case the output of the previous layer the encoder each position the encoder can attend to positions the previous layer of the encoder similarly selfattention layers the decoder allow each position the decoder to attend to positions the decoder up to including that position we need to prevent leftward information flow the decoder to preserve the autoregressive property we implement this inside of scaled dotproduct attention by masking out setting to oo values the input of the softmax which correspond to illegal connections see figure positionwise feedforward networks addition to attention sublayers each of the layers our encoder decoder contains fully connected feedforward network which is applied to each position separately identically this consists of two linear transformations with relu activation between ffnz maxw bw bo while the linear transformations are the same across different positions they use different parameters from layer to layer another way of describing this is as two convolutions with kernel size the dimensionality of input output is dmoder the innerlayer has dimensionality dy embeddings softmax similarly to other sequence transduction models we use learned embeddings to convert the input tokens output tokens to vectors of dimension dmode we use the usual learned linear transfor mation softmax function to convert the decoder output to predicted nexttoken probabilities our model we share the same weight matrix between the two embedding layers the presoftmax linear transformation similar to the embedding layers we multiply those weights by vdmouel positional encoding since our model contains no recurrence no convolution order for the model to make use of the order of the sequence we must inject some information about the relative or absolute position of the,
